com.github.yona168.giraffe.net.messenger.client

Class GClient

  • AbstractScopedPacketChannelComponent
    • com.github.yona168.giraffe.net.messenger.client.GClient
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    CanProcessPackets, Client, Toggled

    public class GClient
extends AbstractScopedPacketChannelComponent
implements Client

    The default implementation of interface Client. For internal packets, this uses the opcode identifier of INTERNAL_OPCODE. Thus, NOTHING else should be registered under that opcode. Further, any implementation of interface Server that uses this class should send a interface SendablePacket made EXACTLY like this one:

        writeByte(Constants.HANDSHAKE_SUB_IDENTIFIER)
    writeUUID(uuidToSend)

    The UUID sent will be set to GClient.getSessionUUID, thus establishing the same UUID by both the Server and Client. Other than this requirement, this class is fit for use with any interface Server implementation, or truly, even anything above that.

    This implementation uses Component for enabling/disabling.

    This class is also used as the interface Client implementation Server-side. Thus, some things work differently on both ends. These differences are determined based on the constructor used. As such, to make that more explicit, instances should be created through GClient.Companion.newServerside and GClient.Companion.newClientside

    The differences are as follows:

    1. server-side clients CANNOT be re-enabled, whereas client-side ones can.

    2. When they disable, server-side clients will NOT disable their packetProcessor. It is assumed that they all share one packet processor from the server. If this is not the case with your server implementation, simply use GClient.onDisable to cancel it.

    Note that this implementation expects packets to be structured as follows:

    1. Opcode of the packet (of type Opcode).

    2. Size of the packet (of type Size).

    3. The rest of the bytes. Thus, any bytes sent with a interface SendablePacket should reflect this pattern. class QueuedOpSendablePacket does this.

    See Also:

      • write

        public java.util.concurrent.CompletableFuture<java.lang.Integer> write(SendablePacket packet)

        Launches a coroutine that writes the bytes from a interface SendablePacket to this GClient.getSocketChannel. SendablePacket.build is called to obtain a ByteBuffer, which is then read in its entirety into the channel. The controller ensures that coroutines wait for the preceding one to complete before writing, in order to avoid errors. This process is asynchronous.

        Parameters:
        packet - the interface SendablePacket to build and send.
        See Also:
        interface SendablePacket, GClient.getSocketChannel, SendablePacket.build, ByteBuffer
